T1  - Nonlinearity and the Study of Organizations
AU  - Piehl, Dewayne
Y1  - 1974/12/01
PY  - 1974
DA  - 1974/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255652
DO  - 10.5465/255652
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 760
EP  - 767
VL  - 17
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article looks at a study which explores organizational behavior for nonlinear relationships. The use of linear theories and statistics within research design is discussed. Examples of nonlinarity are given. Graphs displaying nonlinear relationships are presented. Correlations between the proportion of time spent on technical work and the level of performance are considered. The author notes the need for adequate supervision to meet productivity standards. It is concluded that the benefits of exploring nonlinear relationships justify the associated costs.
AB  - The article looks at a study which explores organizational behavior for nonlinear relationships. The use of linear theories and statistics within research design is discussed. Examples of nonlinarity are given. Graphs displaying nonlinear relationships are presented. Correlations between the proportion of time spent on technical work and the level of performance are considered. The author notes the need for adequate supervision to meet productivity standards. It is concluded that the benefits of exploring nonlinear relationships justify the associated costs.
